root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims familyName

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims citizenship
Type: array

The Jurisdiction that has conferred citizenship rights on the Person such as the right to vote, to receive certain protection from the community or the issuance of a passport. Citizenship is information needed by many cross-border use cases and is a legal status as opposed to the more culturally-focussed and less well-defined term 'nationality'.

Each item of this array must be:

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims citizenship jurisdictionDef
Type: object

The limits or territory within which authority may be exercised.

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims citizenship citizenship items id
Type: stringFormat: URI

A reference in the form of a Uniform Resource Identifier to the Jurisdiction.

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims citizenship citizenship items name
Type: string

A string of characters that represents a Jurisdiction. The name is simply a string that identifies the Jurisdiction, typically a country, with or without a language tag.

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims nationalities
Type: array of string

End-User's nationalities using ICAO 3-letter codes [ICAO-Doc9303], e.g., "USA" or "JPN". 2-letter ICAO codes MAY be used in some circumstances for compatibility reasons. (reference: eKYC) Nationality is more culturally-focused and less well-defined than citizenship. A person can have one or more nationalities.

Each item of this array must be:

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims nationalities nationalities items
Type: stringFormat: ICAO 3-letter code

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims dateOfBirth
Type: stringFormat: date

Defines date of birth of the credential subject, represented as an ISO 8601:2004 [ISO8601â€‘2004] YYYY-MM-DD format. The year MAY be 0000, indicating that it is omitted. To represent only the year, YYYY format is allowed. Note that depending on the underlying platform's date related function, providing just year can result in varying month and day, so the implementers need to take this factor into account to correctly process the dates. Date SHOULD be entered in accordance with the Gregorian calendar.

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf addressDef
Type: object

A spatial object that in a human-readable way identifies a fixed location. See: https://semiceu.github.io/Core-Location-Vocabulary/releases/2.00/#Address

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 addressArea
Type: string

The name of a geographic area that groups Addresses. This would typically be part of a city, a neighbourhood or village, e.g. Montmartre. Address area is not an administrative unit.

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 addressID
Type: string

A globally unique identifier for each instance of an Address. The concept of adding a globally unique identifier for each instance of an address is a crucial part of the INSPIRE data spec. A number of EU countries have already implemented an ID (a UUID) in their Address Register/gazetteer, among them Denmark. OASIS xAL also includes an address identifier. It is the address Identifier that allows an address to be represented in a format other than INSPIRE whilst remaining conformant to the Core Vocabulary

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 administrativeUnit
Type: array of object

A detailed administrative unit organized in a hierarchy. This class should be used whenever a classification mechanism is in place, in alternative to the properties adminUnitL1 and adminUnitL2 of the Address class which allow free text.

Each item of this array must be:

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 administrativeUnit administrativeUnit items
Type: object

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 administrativeUnitLevel1
Type: string

The name of the uppermost level of the address, almost always a country.

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 administrativeUnitLevel2
Type: string

The name of a secondary level/region of the address, usually a county, state or other such area that typically encompasses several localities.

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 fullAddress
Type: string

The complete address written as a string. Use of this property is recommended as it will not suffer any misunderstandings that might arise through the breaking up of an address into its component parts. This property is analogous to vCard's label property but with two important differences: (1) formatting is not assumed so that, unlike vCard label, it may not be suitable to print this on an address label, (2) vCard's label property has a domain of vCard Address; the fullAddress property has no such restriction. An example of a full address is "Champ de Mars, 5 Avenue Anatole France, 75007 Paris, France".

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 locatorDesignator
Type: string

A number or sequence of characters that uniquely identifies the locator within the relevant scope. In simpler terms, this is the building number, apartment number, etc. For an address such as "Flat 3, 17 Bridge Street", the locator is "flat 3, 17".

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 locatorName
Type: string

Proper noun(s) applied to the real world entity identified by the locator. The locator name could be the name of the property or complex, of the building or part of the building, or it could be the name of a room inside a building. The key difference between a locator and a locator name is that the latter is a proper name and is unlikely to include digits.For example, "Shumann, Berlaymont" is a meeting room within the European Commission headquarters for which locator name is more appropriate than locator.

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 postCode
Type: string

The code created and maintained for postal purposes to identify a subdivision of addresses and postal delivery points. Post codes are common elements in many countries' postal address systems. One of the many post codes of Paris is for example "75000".

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 postName
Type: string

A name created and maintained for postal purposes to identify a subdivision of addresses and postal delivery points. Usually a city, for example "Paris".

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 postOfficeBox
Type: string

A location designator for a postal delivery point at a post office, usually a number. INSPIRE's name for this is "postalDeliveryIdentifier" for which it uses the locator designator property with a type attribute of that name. This vocabulary separates out the Post Office Box for greater independence of technology. An example post office box number is "9383".

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims domicile anyOf item 1 thoroughfare
Type: string

The name of a passage or way through from one location to another. A thoroughfare is usually a street, but it might be a waterway or some other feature. For example, "Avenue des Champs-Ã‰lysÃ©es".

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims residency
Type: array

Jurisdiction where the Person has their dwelling. A Person's fixed, permanent, and principal home for legal purposes, the place (especially the house) in which a person officially lives or resides. A Person has one, multiple or even no residency status. Multiple residencies are recorded as multiple instances of the residency.

Each item of this array must be:

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims gender
Type: string

The identities, expressions and societal roles of the Person. The gender of an individual should be recorded using a controlled vocabulary that is appropriate for the specific context. In some cases, the chromosomal or physical state of an individual will be more important than the gender that they express, in others the reverse will be true. What is always important is that the controlled vocabulary used to describe an individual's gender is stated explicitly. Text or URI.

root allOf item 1 credentialSubject allOf item 0 claims pictureURI
Type: stringFormat: URI

URL of the End-User's profile picture. This URL MUST refer to an image file (for example, a PNG, JPEG, or GIF image file), rather than to a Web page containing an image. Note that this URL SHOULD specifically reference a profile photo of the End-User suitable for displaying when describing the End-User, rather than an arbitrary photo taken by the End-User. (OIDC core)
